That’s the brilliance of the song. @richardmarx tricks you into half-hearing it as pleasant background noise but the story it tells is deeply disturbing. When it’s done you feel like a friendly stranger at a bar just obliquely confessed to murder while buying you a drink.

Anyway, @richardmarx is a GREAT Twitter follow, and his catalog is deceptively catchy and ear-wormy that, like Dan Fogelberg and Phil Collins, hides as much wicked humor & cynicism as Elvis Costello and the Pixies.

What I like most about “Hazard” is how @richardmarx doesn’t let us off the hook — the narrator is BEYOND unreliable and the prettiness of the vocal and guitars are a stand-in for a possible psychopath’s disarming charm in manipulating the telling of the story.

It’s deceptively tuneful and catchy, but tells a story as grim and gritty as Primus’ “My Name Is Mud” or The Chills’ “Pink Frost.” @richardmarx has such effortless song craft — the vocals and melody are so gorgeous you miss how disturbing the lyrics are.

It should also be noted how, in 1992, radio-friendly, hit-machine @richardmarx wrote and recorded the #1 song “Hazard” — a beyond-dark murder ballad he somehow smuggled to the top of the Adult Contemporary Charts.
I can’t get over how funny, angry and feisty @richardmarx is on Twitter.

7/ The whole thing where Tom talks about people not eating bread. There are a couple of jokes IN there yes but the big laugh is from how exhausted Tom sounds when he just keeps repeating, “They...don’t...eat...BREAD.” His brain has fritzed out and it’s the PERFECT OBSERVATION.

6/ Another thing about @tompapa — he finds those moments where you’re so overwhelmed with the enormity of life you CAN’T nail the “clever thought” on a subject, and the FAILURE to arrive there is where the hilarity and brilliance are. I’ve never seen anything like it.

5/ Sorry for the gushing thread but, again, @tompapa’s new @netflix special is TRULY something special. Tom is smuggling some deep ruminations inside what seems like goofy, top-of-his-head ranting and it’s a wonder to watch.

4/ And @tompapa’s riffs on mortality, sexism, parenting and life itself blindside you with their darkness because it they all sound so gentle and hilarious. I’m going to watch it again on the plane right now to see if I can figure out how he pulls it off.

3/ What I’m about to say is going to sound negative but it’s not: @tompapa doesn’t have “jokes” anymore. It’s one deceptively sustained, bizarre “pep talk” that has more laughs per minute that most comedians can pack into a whole set.
2/ I’ve always been a fan of @tompapa but he’s gone through some kind of “Zen master” evolution these last few years.
